{"id":"2101.11541","submitter":"Mark Lewis","authors":"Shawn T. Burkett and Mark L. Lewis","title":"Partial GVZ-groups","comments":"11 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Following the literature, a group $G$ is called a group of central type if\n$G$ has an irreducible character that vanishes on $G\\setminus Z(G)$. Motivated\nby this definition, we say that a character $\\chi\\in {\\rm Irr}(G)$ has central\ntype if $\\chi$ vanishes on $G\\setminus Z(\\chi)$, where $Z(\\chi)$ is the center\nof $\\chi$. Groups where every irreducible character has central type have been\nstudied previously under the name GVZ-groups (and several other names) in the\nliterature. In this paper, we study the groups $G$ that possess a nontrivial,\nnormal subgroup $N$ such that every character of $G$ either contains $N$ in its\nkernel or has central type. The structure of these groups is surprisingly\nlimited and has many aspects in common with both central type groups and\nGVZ-groups.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 27 Jan 2021 16:53:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-28"}
